review_blob: Another quality beer from Laurelwood. Bottle from Johns Market poured a beautiful red color with a nice white head. Good lacing. A little hoppy for an amber. More like a I.R.A. Still, a well balanced beer.

aroma of fresh barley- -  red in color with a thin white head good lacing-  caramel notes without being sweet-  lingerling hops that dry out the palate- almost a slight spicyfinish- good beer that presents a different taste with each sip- nice presentation- would drink again
did not enjoy this beer and i would not recommend  this beer to anyone- it is extra special, but i dont think that is a good thing in this beer case

in the bottle from johns market in PDX- not much  flavor- overly carbonated-  hops linger on the palate-  aroma sweet, but borderline sour-  not the comfprting flavor and smoothness that one can get from the style- dissapointing, couldnt even finish it!

purchased the bottle at johns market in portland strictly for its name-  Bigfoot-  (a legend in the northwest-)  poured nicely into a tasting glass with good lacing and head- cherry red/ coppery colored-  sweet on the palate initially, but definately a bit too much lingering hop tanginess for my personal liking-  definatly a one-beer beer-  warms your belly up!

On tap at the NE 51st & Sandy location. WOW. Finally a beer worth getting a Coffee flavor isnt over bearing considering the strong coffee aroma. A very well balanced beer. 3 days in a growler hasnt harmed this beer at all. Delicious. Should be year round beer, not just a seasonal.
Laurelwood has a great growler punch card program so this growler was only $1.
Get it while it lasts. Perfect score for a perfect beer.

A true belly warmer. Bottle poured a dark brown nearly black. Nose essence of Rogue Hazelnut-Brown, in a good way. Chocolate and Spruce aromas as well. 
Well balanced delicious beer. It would be a great one for the Holiday Ale festival in Portland.
Which came first, Laughing Dog or Lucky Lab??? Very similar logo.
beer_name: Laughing Dog Cold Nose Winter Ale

review_blob:
Winter on the Oregon Coast is what this beer truly is. Wow. Big beer. Poured into a wine glass at the Brewery Jan. 10, 2008...Winter getaway.
Pelican Pub & Brewery deScription:
"Slightly hazy dark orange color. Vinous, oaky character highlighted by aromas of dried cherries and vanilla. Moderately tart character with tannin in the finish shows the pinot noir influence. "9.2% abv.
beer_name: Pelican Stormwatchers Winterfest (2003) Pinot Barrel Aged

review_blob: Beautiful dark beer, bottle poured with thick, creamy brown head. Smooth + Tasty. Slight hop linger with minimal hop presence. Chocolate and cherries, what a delicious beer.
Its one-beer-beer. Great Brewery, good beer. Beautiful pour. A little too hoppy for my liking, but a northwest beer it is. Dont miss the brewery in McMinnville, Oregon.

bottle poured into a  glass-  presence of alcohol on the nose, but overall smooth with a clean crisp finish-  it feels like a northwest brown -  chocolate finish without too much hops-  could definately drink another!

22 oz. Limited Release bottling. Hoppy nose, with a nicely balanced taste. Malty yet crisp. Dry hop?
Festive and warming without the spice. Dangerously smoooooth. 
Dont Drink and Bike!!!

Special Bottling, gift from Dave at Full Sail. Better memories of this beer on tap than the bottled experience. Poured into a stemmed glass, giving off a very bready aroma. Pizza-bready and sweet like tomatoes. Strong upfront flavor. Wow. 8.4% and it tastes like it.
beer_name: Full Sail Special Anniversary Doppel X

review_blob: Humbug! Whoop! One fine beer. Well balanced Winter warmer. Bottle-poured into a Trappist glass. Very nice lacing with a lasting head. Clove/Pine flavors give a real spicy, Christmas  feeling. Excellent seasonal brew. One Good Ebenezer leads to another...

12 oz. bottle...W 07 to celebrate Josh Beckett getting his 7th W for the Red Sox. 
Poured a ruby brown color with a strong, citrus hop aroma. Kinda sweet and malty with a big, crisp hop finish.

Also sampled at Blooms and Brews Fest, but this isnt the first time tasting it. 
Medium brown/ dark amber hue. Medium creamy head, with little linger or lacing. Very mild, malty brew with very little hop presence. A well balanced beer. Great after a long hike.

(12 oz. bottle)
Traditional Deschutes dry-hopped ale. Mild citrus notes with a clean, dry finish. Light copper color with medium to light head retention.
Will get it again.

(12 oz. bottle)
A rich and flavorful amber without too much malty sweetness. Clean and crisp subtle hop finish. 
Another quality product of Deschutes Brewing.
